<h3 id="digital-history--data-viz">Digital history / data viz</h3>
<p>As a grad student I created a project applying various digital humanities tools and approaches to do a “distant reading” of slave narratives in UNC’s “Documenting the American South” online library.</p>
<ul>
  <li><a href="http://dighist.fas.harvard.edu/courses/2015/HIST1993/exhibits/show/modeling-equiano/project-overview">Topic Modeling Equiano and the Slave Narrative Genre</a></li>
</ul>

<h3 id="harvard-kennedy-school">Harvard Kennedy School</h3>
<p>Before my teaching career, I worked at the Kennedy School’s Ash Center for Democratic Governance and Innovation as a research assistant and writer for the Project on Municipal Innovation.</p>

<ul>
  <li><a href="https://datasmart.ash.harvard.edu/news/article/from-comment-cards-to-sentiment-mining-301">From Comment Cards to Sentiment Mining</a></li>
  <li><a href="https://datasmart.ash.harvard.edu/news/article/data-standards-314">With Form Comes Function</a></li>
  <li><a href="https://datasmart.ash.harvard.edu/news/article/keynote-415">Managing for the Soul of the City</a></li>
  <li><a href="https://datasmart.ash.harvard.edu/news/article/regulating-rideshares-429">Regulating Rideshares</a></li>
  <li><a href="https://datasmart.ash.harvard.edu/news/article/louisville-performance-improvement-463">Stretch Goals</a></li>
</ul>

<p>I also contributed reporting and writing to a few chapters in <a href="https://www.wiley.com/en-us/The+Responsive+City%3A+Engaging+Communities+Through+Data+Smart+Governance-p-9781118910900"><em>The Responsive City</em></a>. And I designed the cover!</p>

<h3 id="harvard-gazette">Harvard Gazette</h3>
